        "body": "Verse 1 consists entirely of two parallel imperatives addressed to two parallel universal categories. *Halal* (praise) and *shavach* (laud, commend) are not synonyms chosen for poetic variety alone — they carry distinct semantic weight. *Halal* in the Piel stem is the boastful, celebratory, unself-conscious declaration of someone's glory; it is the root of 'Hallelujah' and it is what Israel does before YHWH in temple worship. *Shavach* accents the verbal, testimonial dimension — to commend publicly, to speak well of someone before others. Together the two verbs command both celebratory worship and public testimony: the nations are to both exult in YHWH and declare His excellence to one another.\n\nThe two objects — *kol-goyim* (all nations) and *kol-ha'ummim* (all peoples) — form the OT's standard comprehensive merism for non-Israelite humanity. *Goy* is the political-national category (kingdoms, states, empires); *ummah* is the ethnic-tribal category (clans, language groups, kinship communities). By using both, the psalm leaves no category of humanity outside the command. There is no nation too powerful to be included, no tribe too obscure to be summoned.\n\nThe force of the imperatives deserves full attention. These are not invitations or wishful longings; they are commands. The psalmist does not say 'It would be wonderful if the nations praised the LORD.' He commands them to do so — the same grammatical force as the Ten Commandments. This means the nations' failure to praise YHWH is not ignorance or cultural difference; it is moral failure, a violation of the first commandment obligation owed to the Creator. Paul makes exactly this point in Romans 1:21: the nations 'knew God' and 'did not honor Him as God or give thanks.' Psalm 117 is the positive command of which Romans 1:21 names the violation.\n\nHistorically, the context of this psalm's use in the Egyptian Hallel (Psalms 113-118) is Passover. At Passover, Israel celebrated its own liberation from the nations (Egypt specifically) — and yet this psalm within that liturgy summons those same nations to praise. The liturgical placement is itself a theological statement: the God who liberated Israel from the nations is the same God who summons the nations into Israel's worship.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Halal* (Piel imperative) — to boast, to celebrate loudly; the intensive stem signals vigorous, public, unrestrained praise. *Shavach* — to commend, to laud, to speak approvingly; carries connotations of public testimony. *Goy* (nations) vs. *ummah* (peoples) — standard OT merism covering the full range of human community outside the covenant."
