        "number": 2,
        "title": "Chesed prevailing, emet everlasting — the two-attribute theology of universal praise",
        "range": "117:2a-b",
        "excerpt": "For His lovingkindness is great toward us, and the truth of the LORD is everlasting.",
        "body": "The 'For' (*ki*) of verse 2 is the theological pivot of the entire psalm. The command of verse 1 is not grounded in the nations' subjective religious experience, their spiritual searching, or even their observation of creation (though Romans 1:20 presses that ground elsewhere). It is grounded in the specific character of a specific God: YHWH's *chesed* and *emet*. The nations are commanded to praise because these two realities are true.\n\n*Chesed* is the single most important covenant word in the Hebrew OT. Katharine Doob Sakenfeld's classic study (*The Meaning of Hesed in the Hebrew Bible*, 1978) established that *chesed* encompasses the full range of committed, loyal, obligation-keeping love between covenant partners — with the crucial asymmetry that in the divine-human relationship, God is always the superior party who maintains *chesed* downward to the inferior party who has no claim upon it except the covenant itself. In Psalm 117, *chesed* is modified by *gavar* — a verb used of warriors overcoming opponents, of floodwaters prevailing (Genesis 7:18), of armies winning battles. God's *chesed* is not gentle background warmth; it is an overcoming force that has prevailed through Israel's entire history of faithlessness, exile, and return. This is the *chesed* that held when Israel broke covenant at Sinai (Exodus 34:6-7), held through the exile that Psalm 137 mourns, and held in the return that Ezra and Nehemiah document.\n\nThe *chesed* is specifically 'toward us' — *alenu*, 'upon us, over us.' The preposition is covenantal and directional: God's overcoming love has been directed upon Israel as its object and recipient. The nations observe this. They have been witnesses of what God has done to sustain, rescue, discipline, and restore Israel across centuries. That testimony of *chesed-in-history* is the nations' warrant for praise.\n\n*Emet* — from the root *aman* (to be firm, established; the same root as the liturgical 'Amen') — is God's reliability, His truth-as-faithfulness. Where *chesed* is relational and warm, *emet* is firm and structural. Together they are the two load-bearing columns of God's covenant character. The pairing appears at the supreme self-revelation moment of the OT: 'The LORD, the LORD God, compassionate and gracious, slow to anger, and abounding in *chesed* and *emet*' (Exodus 34:6, NASB). Psalm 117 presents these same two attributes as the complete and sufficient grounds for universal praise — not in an abstract theological treatise, but in two Hebrew words.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chesed* — the OT's richest covenant-love word, occurring over 240 times; *gavar* (prevails) applied to *chesed* intensifies it from sentiment to conquering force. *Emet* — from *aman* (to be firm); its cognates include *amen* and *emunah* (faith/faithfulness). *Olam* — beyond the visible horizon; used of the Abrahamic covenant (Genesis 17:7), the Davidic covenant (2 Samuel 7:13), and the Levitical priesthood (Numbers 25:13) — here of God's *emet* itself."
