        "number": 3,
        "title": "Paul's catena — Psalm 117 as eschatological prophecy of the Gentile mission",
        "range": "117:1-2",
        "excerpt": "Praise the LORD, all nations; Laud Him, all peoples!",
        "body": "The New Testament's most decisive reading of Psalm 117 is Paul's citation in Romans 15:11. Romans 15:7-12 is among the NT's densest concentrations of OT testimony about the Gentiles. Paul's purpose is to demonstrate from the OT itself that the Gentile mission is not a Plan B improvised after Israel's rejection of the Messiah — it is the original intent of the covenant announced to Abraham. He builds a four-text catena: Psalm 18:49 (David glorifying God among the Gentiles), Deuteronomy 32:43 (Gentiles rejoicing with Israel), Psalm 117:1 (all nations and peoples praising the Lord), and Isaiah 11:10 (the Root of Jesse as a banner for the Gentiles).\n\nPaul's placement of Psalm 117:1 in this chain is climactic. He reads the psalm's universal imperative not merely as liturgical aspiration but as prophetic announcement: the nations *will* praise, and they will praise because the Christ whom Paul proclaims has made it possible. Christ 'has become a servant to the circumcision on behalf of the truth of God to confirm the promises given to the fathers, and for the Gentiles to glorify God for His mercy' (Romans 15:8-9). The two divine attributes of Psalm 117:2 (*emet* = truth, *chesed* = mercy/lovingkindness) reappear in Paul's summary in Romans 15:8-9 as precisely the two realities Christ's servanthood confirms and displays. Paul is doing what no mere prooftexter does — he is reading the psalm in its canonical depth and showing that the Christ-event is the fulfillment-agent of what the psalm commands.\n\nThe canonical trajectory from Psalm 117 to Revelation is equally striking. In Revelation 7:9-10, the consummation of history is described as a great multitude which no one could count, from every nation (*ethnos*) and all tribes and peoples (*laos*) and tongues, standing before the throne and before the Lamb, crying out salvation to our God and to the Lamb. The Greek words for 'nations' and 'peoples' in Revelation 7:9 are the LXX equivalents of the Hebrew *goyim* and *ummim* of Psalm 117:1. John sees the same universal assembly the psalmist commanded — now actually assembled, now actually praising, before the throne of the Lamb whose *chesed* has prevailed and whose *emet* has endured. Psalm 117 is not merely a command; it is a preview.\n\n> **Greek note (LXX / NT).** The Septuagint translates *kol-goyim* as *panta ta ethnē* (all the Gentiles/nations) — the exact phrase Paul quotes in Romans 15:11. *Chesed* is rendered *eleos* (mercy, compassion) in LXX Psalm 116:2 (= MT 117:2). *Emet* is rendered *alētheia* (truth). Paul's Romans 15:8-9 summary — Christ confirms 'the *alētheia* of God' and causes Gentiles to glorify God for His '*eleos*' — deliberately echoes these two LXX words from Psalm 117."
