        "number": 4,
        "title": "The shortest psalm, the largest theology — canon, center, and eschatological goal",
        "range": "117:1-2",
        "excerpt": "Praise the LORD! [Hallelujah]",
        "body": "Psalm 117's closing *Hallelujah* connects it to the Psalter's own eschatological trajectory. The Psalter's final five psalms (146-150) all open and close with *Hallelujah* — they are the 'Great Hallel' that brings the entire Psalter to its doxological conclusion. Psalm 150's final verse ('Let everything that has breath praise the LORD') is the Psalter's omega point. Psalm 117's *Hallelujah* anticipates that ending in miniature: the two-verse psalm at the center of the canon models what the five closing psalms unfold in full.\n\nThe theological claim of Psalm 117's canonical placement deserves sustained reflection. The human Bible-reader who opens to the exact middle of Scripture finds not a battle narrative, not a genealogy, not a legal code, but a universal summons to praise grounded in divine *chesed* and *emet*. This is the canonical statement that the chief end of God in redemptive history — as Jonathan Edwards argued at length in *The End for Which God Created the World* — is His own glory expressed through the worshiping community of all nations. The psalm does not make praise a response to something more important; it makes everything else the servant of praise.\n\nFor the preacher and the student, the psalm raises a diagnostic question that its two verses do not answer but only sharpen: why are the nations not praising? The psalm assumes YHWH's *chesed* and *emet* are publicly visible in covenant history. Romans 1:18-21 answers the silence: the nations suppress the truth in unrighteousness. Romans 15:7-12 answers the solution: Christ the Servant displays the *emet* and *chesed* of God in His own person, making the praise of the nations actually possible for the first time since Adam. The Gentile church's Sunday worship is Psalm 117 being fulfilled — the nations streaming to praise the God of Israel through the Mediator who is David's greater Son. Every congregation of former pagans lifting voice to YHWH is a partial fulfillment of this psalm's command and a foretaste of Revelation 7:9-10's complete fulfillment.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Hallelujah* — the fusion of *hallelu* (Piel imperative plural of *halal*: praise!) with *Yah* (the shortened form of YHWH). It appears 24 times in the Psalter, concentrated in the final five psalms and the Egyptian Hallel (Psalms 113-118). Its Psalter distribution is not random — it marks the liturgical high-points of Israel's worship and the eschatological direction of the Psalter's own narrative arc."
